article.headline: Sonics win battle of boards, game against Suns
article.linkText: Sonics pound glass to hand Suns costly loss
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Rashard Lewis scored 25 of his 29 points in the second half as the Seattle SuperSonics beat Phoenix 82-73 Monday night, an ugly home loss that could prove costly in the Suns' fight for the final Western Conference playoff spot. Ray Allen added 22 points for the Sonics, who have won three of four. Reggie Evans grabbed 13 rebounds as Seattle dominated the boards 50-36. Stephon Marbury had 22 points and 10 assists as the Suns matched their season-low in scoring. They also scored 73 in their season-opener at Seattle. Shawn Marion added 15 points on 5-for-16 shooting. The loss by Phoenix clinched a playoff spot for the San Antonio Spurs. The victory left Seattle just 2½ games behind the Suns with 11 to play. Phoenix entered the game tied with Houston for the eighth and final playoff spot in the West. Lewis, who was 10-for-13 shooting in the second half, scored 16 of Seattle's first 18 points in the third quarter as the Sonics built a 53-40 lead with 6:45 left in the quarter. Seattle led 61-53 entering the fourth quarter. Marion sank two 3-pointers as the Suns outscored the Sonics 10-3 to start the fourth quarter to cut Seattle's lead to 64-63 on Marbury's inside basket with 8:16 to play. But Seattle scored the next seven points, two baskets by Lewis and a 3-pointer by Allen, to go up 71-63 with 5:13 to play. Marion's 3-pointer with 3:58 to play cut the lead to 75-71, but Kevin Ollie scored, then Brent Barry sank a 3-pointer and the Sonics were safely up 80-71 with two minutes to play. The Sonics shot 26 percent in the first half and still trailed only 37-35 at the break, thanks to a 10-4 advantage in offensive rebounds and eight Suns' turnovers. Seattle finished at 37 percent shooting for the game. Game notes
Charles Barkley, who has reconciled his long dispute with Suns owner Jerry Colangelo, received a huge cheer when he was introduced with other former Phoenix players before the game as part of the team's ``retro night.'' It was his first public appearance at a Suns home game since his retirement from the NBA. ... The first game in Suns' history was against Seattle on Oct. 28, 1968. ... Seattle is 11-6 since trading Gary Payton to Milwaukee. ... Other than Lewis, the rest of the Sonics made 16 of 60 shots. ... Houston owns the tiebreaker with Phoenix. ... Amare Stoudemire, bothered by a sore ankle, played just 21 minutes for the Suns.
